Package com.rb.nonbiz.collections

Class IidMapVisitors

java.lang.Object
com.rb.nonbiz.collections.IidMapVisitors
public class IidMapVisitors
extends java.lang.Object
Support for visiting IidMap objects - possible multiple ones.

This it to help focus on what to do on each case (e.g. an object appears on only the 1st, or only the 2nd, or both maps) by only having to supply a lambda for each case, without having to do if/then/else-type logic.

    • visitInstrumentsOfTwoIidMaps

      public static <VL,​ VR> void visitInstrumentsOfTwoIidMaps​(IidMap<VL> leftMap, IidMap<VR> rightMap, IidMapVisitors.TwoIidMapsVisitor<VL,​VR> visitor)
      When you have 2 IidMaps, this lets you perform 3 different actions for items that are only in the left map, only in the right map, or in both maps. It lets you specify a bit more cleanly (via the TwoIidMapsVisitor) what to do in those 3 different cases.
      See Also:
      RBMapVisitors.visitItemsOfTwoRBMaps(com.rb.nonbiz.collections.RBMap<K, VL>, com.rb.nonbiz.collections.RBMap<K, VR>, com.rb.nonbiz.collections.RBMapVisitors.TwoRBMapsVisitor<K, VL, VR>)

    • visitInstrumentsOfThreeIidMaps

      public static <V1,​ V2,​ V3> void visitInstrumentsOfThreeIidMaps​(IidMap<V1> map1, IidMap<V2> map2, IidMap<V3> map3, QuadriConsumer<InstrumentId,​java.util.Optional<V1>,​java.util.Optional<V2>,​java.util.Optional<V3>> quadriConsumer)
      When you have 3 IidMaps, this lets you perform 7 = 2 ^ 3 - 1 different actions for items based on whether items exist in the {1st, 2nd, 3rd} map, respectively. It's not possible for an item to exist in NO map, by definition, since we're looking at the set union of all InstrumentId keys from all 3 maps. Hence the minus 1 in the formula above. It lets you specify a bit more cleanly what to do in those 3 different cases.
      See Also:
      RBMapVisitors.visitItemsOfTwoRBMaps(com.rb.nonbiz.collections.RBMap<K, VL>, com.rb.nonbiz.collections.RBMap<K, VR>, com.rb.nonbiz.collections.RBMapVisitors.TwoRBMapsVisitor<K, VL, VR>)

    • visitInstrumentsOfTwoIidMapsAssumingSubset

      public static <VL,​ VR> void visitInstrumentsOfTwoIidMapsAssumingSubset​(IidMap<VL> leftMap, IidMap<VR> rightMap, TriConsumer<InstrumentId,​VL,​VR> inBothConsumer, java.util.function.BiConsumer<InstrumentId,​VR> rightOnlyConsumer)
      When you have 2 IidMaps and the keys of the first are a subset of the keys of the second, this lets you perform one action for the entries that appear in both, or a different action for the entries that only appear in the second map. Note: if the keys of the two maps match, then the first is still technically a "subset" of the second, and this method will not throw an exception.

    • visitItemsOfIidSetAndIidMap
